<chapter xml:id="function2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
	<title>Injections and Surjections</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>


Let <m>X,Y,Z</m> be finite sets, perhaps of different sizes. Let <m>f:X \rightarrow Y</m> and <m>g:Y \rightarrow Z</m>.

Decide whether each of the following statements is <em> true</em> or <em> false</em>.
		<ul>
			<li>
			<p>
 If the statement is <em> true</em>, provide a proof. (It will be easier to prove the contrapositive.)
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 If the statement is <em> false</em>, provide a counterexample.
			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>


	</p>
	</introduction>
	<exercises>
		<title>Practice Problems</title>

		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
 If <m>g \circ f</m> is injective then <m>f</m> is injective.

<!--solution>
<p>

<em> true</em>. We will give TWO proofs.

<em>First, we prove the contrapositive statement.</em>

If <m>f</m> is not injective then <m>g \circ f</m> is not injective.

<em> Know:</em> There exist <m> x_1, x_2 \in X</m> such that <m>x_1 \neq x_2</m> and <m>f(x_1) = f(x_2)</m>.

<em> Show:</em> There exist <m> a_1, a_2 \in X</m> such that <m>a_1 \neq a_2</m> and <m>g \circ f(a_1) = g \circ  f(a_2)</m>.


		<ul>
			<li>
			<p>
 Pick  <m>x_1, x_2 \in X</m> such that <m>x_1 \neq x_2</m> and <m>f(x_1) = f(x_2)</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Then we have <m>x_1 \neq x_2</m> and
\[
g \circ f (x_1) = g(f(x_1)) = g(f(x_2)) = g \circ f(x_2).
\]
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 In other words, taking <m>a_1=x_1</m> and <m>a_2=x_2</m> satisfies our <em> Show</em> statement.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Therefore <m>g \circ f: X \rightarrow Z</m> is not injective.


			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

<em>Next, we prove the original statement.</em>

<em> Know:</em> If <m> x_1 \neq x_2 </m> then  <m>g \circ f(x_1) \neq g \circ f(x_2)</m>.

<em> Show:</em> If <m> x_1 \neq x_2 </m> then  <m> f(x_1) \neq   f(x_2)</m>.

		<ul>
			<li>
			<p>
 Pick any <m>x_1 \neq x_2</m>. We know that <m>g \circ f(x_1) \neq g \circ f(x_2).</m>
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Let <m>y_1=f(x_1)</m> and <m>y_2 =   f(x_2)</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Then <m>g \circ f(x_1) \neq g \circ f(x_2)</m> is equivalent to <m>g (y_1) \neq g (y_2).</m>
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Since <m>g</m> is well defined function, we must have <m>y_1 \neq y_2</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 This is the same as saying that <m>f(x_1) \neq f(x_2)</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Therefore <m>f: X \rightarrow Y</m> is  injective.


			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>


</p>
