		<exercise>
			<statement>
				<p>
 If <m>g \circ f</m> is surjective then <m>g</m> is surjective.


<!--solution>
<p>


<em> true.</em> We give two proofs.

<em>First, we prove the contrapositive:</em>


If <m>g</m> is not surjective then <m>g \circ f</m> is not surjective.


<em> Know:</em> There exists <m>z \in Z</m> such that for all <m>y \in Y</m>, <m>g(y) \neq z</m>.

<em> Show:</em> There exists <m>z \in Z</m> such that for all <m>x \in X</m>, <m>g \circ f (x) \neq z</m>.

		<ul>
			<li>
			<p>
 Let <m>f(X) = \{ f(x) \mid x \in X \}</m> be the image of <m>f</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Obviously <m>f(X)</m> is a subset of <m>Y</m>. So for all <m>y \in f(X)</m>, we know that <m>f(y) \neq z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Pick any <m>x \in X</m>. Then <m>g \circ f(x) = g(f(x))</m>. We have <m>f(x) \in Y</m>, and therefore <m>g(f(x)) \neq z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 This proves that <m>g \circ f: X \rightarrow Z</m> is not surjective.

			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>


			</p><p>

<em>Next, we prove the original statement:</em>





<em> Know:</em> For all  <m>z \in Z</m> there exists <m>x \in X</m> such that <m>g \circ f(x) = z</m>.

<em> Show:</em> For all  <m>z \in Z</m> there exists <m>y \in Y</m> such that <m>g (y) = z</m>.

		<ul>
			<li>
			<p>
 Pick any <m>z \in Z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 There is an <m>x \in X</m> such that <m>g \circ f(x) = z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Let <m>y= f(x)</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Then <m>g(y) = g(f(x)) = g \circ f(x) =z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 We found a <m>y \in Y</m> such that <m>g(y)=z</m>.
			</p>
			</li>
			<li>
			<p>
 Therefore <m>g</m> is surjective.
			</p>
			</li>
		</ul>

</p>
</solution-->


